omes skidded from  in  to fewer than  in  forcing the company to whittle its employee staff to  “our thesis was when those markets did recover that they would recover at a faster rate than the national average” recalls president and coo matt zaist pictured left so the firm held on to its sizable book of land which is located in supplyconstrained markets like coastal california where company forecasters believed demand for new homes eventually would rebound with a vengeance and even as it stalled a number of planned building projects the builder continued to slowly acquire land through the downturn that bet started to pay off in  as the builder activated many of those stalled projects and doubled its yearoveryear home sales revenue from  to  securing the builder the no  spot on the  builder  list traditionally a builder for firsttime buyers the firm retooled its product offering during the downturn instead of catering only to cashstrapped young buyers it expanded into the first and secondmoveup markets by the end of last year  percent of its deliveries went to moveup buyers and  percent sold to new homeowners in december  william lyon homes expanded into colorado with the purchase of the bankrupt moveup home builder village homes and since then the firm has invested  million in additional land mostly in infill locations in coastal california and in colorado and las vegas by the start of this year the builder held  lots says ceo bill h lyon pictured right looking ahead says zaist the company anticipates it will increase its community count by north of  percent this year without expanding into new markets “we think  will be a better year for our company and for the industry as a whole” agrees lyon source builder  data learn more about markets featured in this article los angeles ca about the author sharon omalley sharon omalley is a freelance writer based in college park md she has contributed to builder for  years advertisement keywords subject business entrylevel lan